I think I'll pass on this recommendation.  No offense.  :)  I'm not super familiar with decorators yet, and I'm worried that this will be intimidating to other users who want to use this registration functionality, who may be even less familiar with decorator syntax.

Also, I think as written, this will assign the _class_ to the `valid_extra_outputs` dict rather than an _instance_ of that class.  For the `ExtraOutputBuilder`s, we could do it that way: have the class be the thing that is registered and make an instance later when we need it.  

But some of the other things I register use the same class with different initialization parameters for different types.  So I decided it made more sense to have everything register instances rather than classes to be consistent.  I think in the decorator syntax, this would look like:
```
def RegisterExtraOutput(key):
    def decorate(builder):
        valid_extra_outputs[key] = builder

class BadPixBuilder(ExtraOutputBuilder):
    ...

@RegisterExtraOutput("badpix")
BadPixBuilder()
```
which doesn't seem like a big improvement over the existing syntax using the function call.

this will break local environments that do not have $DEIS_BINARY set (I don't run test-integration.sh locally, just boot up my own cluster then run `make -C tests test-full`). Would you mind changing this to:

```
var Deis = os.Getenv("DEIS_BINARY")
if Deis == "" {
    Deis = "deis "
}
```

While we're at it, we should remove the space requirement in $DEIS_BINARY and just update the one reference to this variable :)

```
from ._client_factory import (resource_client_factory, keyvault_client_factory, ...)
```

